article.headline: Owls not intimidated by ranked foe
article.linkText: Rice pushes back, beats Louisiana Tech in OT
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Lauren Neaves wasn't going to be pushed around by
eighth-ranked Louisiana Tech.

"They were a lot more physical than I thought they would be. I
knew I had to fight back," Neaves said after she scored three
points in the final minute of overtime to lead Rice to an 87-84
victory over Louisiana Tech on Monday night.

"I didn't see any reason to be pushed around," Neaves said.
"Everyone on our team played up to her potential. This was a
complete team victory."

Louisiana Tech (8-2, 1-1 Western Athletic Conference) led by as
many as four points in overtime before the game was tied at 82.
Neaves hit the go-ahead free throw and followed with a field goal
with 24 seconds to go.

Tech's Lakiste Barkus cut the margin to 85-84 before Eshombi
Singleton and Elisa Inman made clinching free throws for the Lady
Owls.

Rice coach Cristy McKinney liked the Lady Owls' tough play.

"We played stronger and we played tougher than we have been,"
McKinney said. "This is a huge win for our program and our
basketball team."

Lindsay Maynard, who led Rice (5-6, 1-1) with 18 points, forced
the overtime when she sank one of two free throws with six seconds
left in regulation after Tech was hit with a technical for calling
too many timeouts.

"After I got the first one I was confident that I would make
the second one, but I was tired and I shot it too hard," Maynard
explained.

Neaves scored 17 points for Rice. Anne Peck added 14 and
Michelle Woods 10.

Amisha Carter led Tech with 26 points and 19 rebounds. Erica
Smith-Taylor scored 20 points and Amber Obaze 14.

Tech coach Kurt Budke was not pleased with his team's effort
early in the game.

"I thought we were just going through the motions," Budke
said. "Then we picked it up and played like were are capable of."

After trailing 41-29 at the half, Louisiana Tech chipped away at
the Rice lead, cutting the deficit to 48-45 after five consecutive
points by Carter with 13:32 left.

Rice made it 59-49 with 8:53 left and led 64-54 with 5:06
remaining. The Lady Techsters then scored eight straight points to
reduce the Rice lead to two with 3:17 to play.

The Lady Techsters took their first lead since the opening two
minutes at 67-66 on a basket by Carter with 1:29 left.

The lead changed hands five times and was tied once before Tech
was called for the technical.

"That timeout was my responsibility, but we need to have some
players take some responsibility on their end," Budke said.

Rice led 12-11 with 13:30 left in the first half. The Owls then
outscored the Lady Techsters 19-2 to increase their lead to 31-13.

Smith-Taylor scored eight straight points for Tech to cut the
Rice lead to 31-21 with 6:02 left in the half.

The Owls then outscored the Lady Techsters 8-2 in the final two
minutes of the first half to move ahead 41-29.
